\begin_layout Standard
The pairing will play two crucial roles: opening a gap at the outer wings
 of the dispersion
\color blue
 
\color inherit
where the Zeeman field is unimportant and modifying the gap forming near
 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

.
 The former role eliminates the possibility of high-momentum gapless excitations
, thus leaving only the 
\color purple
chiral
\color inherit
 states near 
\begin_inset Formula $k=0$
\end_inset

 as low energy excitation.
 
\color purple
These states resemble the edge of a topological insulator [??]
\color inherit
.
 The latter role allows us to tune the topological phase transitions essential
 for the production of Majorana fermions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\]

\end_inset

In Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_real}}$
\end_inset

) we show the low energy spectrum specifically for the 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi=\pi$
\end_inset

 case, as a function of the Zeeman field 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 for different scales of the nanowire's length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 We tune 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 from weak fields where we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $C>0$
\end_inset

, up to stronger field where 
\begin_inset Formula $C<0$
\end_inset

, passing through the topological phase transition at 
\begin_inset Formula $C=0$
\end_inset

 case.
 Starting on the left graph of Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_real}}$
\end_inset

) where the nanowire length 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is very long, we see that for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}>0$
\end_inset

 the system is trivially gapped, having its gap decreasing until it reaches
 zero at 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, and then, for 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}<0$
\end_inset

, we see the emergence of two Majorana zero energy modes which are gapped
 from the quasicontinuum due to the topological minigap.
 The energy of the lowest excitation clearly traces the topological transition
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{0}=0$
\end_inset

, producing the phase diagrams show in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:S_real}}$
\end_inset

) as a function of Zeeman energy 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{\text{Z}}$
\end_inset

 and chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 See that, for huge 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 the phase diagram converges to the one shown previously in Fig.(
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ref{fig:Ean}}$
\end_inset

)(*), as it should.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\color purple
The minigap can be shown to be effectively 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-wave, and hence topologically non-trivial.
 They are thus topologically protected states.
 The Majorana length 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi_{M}$
\end_inset

, i.e the extension of the Majorana wavefunction, is the coherence length
 corresponding to the minigap, thus becoming smaller for stronger SO coupling.
 
\end_layout

